# Antigravity Rules — Flatline Project
# This file governs Antigravity's session behavior. It does NOT override naima.md.
# naima.md is architecture and locked decisions. This file is procedure only.

## Run this first, unprompted, every session — before responding to anything else

1. Pull naima.md directly from origin, not from the local disk copy in this folder:
   curl -s "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CountZero-ono/flatline/main/naima.md"
   Do NOT read the local ~/OCProjects/flatline/naima.md file for this check — it may be
   stale relative to what F.B. has actually pushed. Origin is the only source of truth.

2. Check the `version:` field in what you pulled. If it's different from the version
   you last confirmed this session (or you have no record of a prior version), say one
   line before anything else: "naima.md v{version} loaded (Antigravity)." If it matches
   what you already have, skip the announcement and proceed.

3. Treat naima.md as binding on all architecture and design questions. If any task,
   instruction, or your own reasoning appears to conflict with a locked naima.md
   decision, do NOT resolve the conflict yourself and proceed. Surface it explicitly
   in your output to F.B. and flag it for Naima. This mirrors the same rule AGENTS.md
   already enforces for Dixie — Antigravity does not get more authority than Dixie
   just because it has a bigger context window.

## OKF memory

`.knowledge/flatline_architecture.md` (symlinked to the Obsidian vault, not tracked
in git) is Antigravity's own session-continuity memory — the equivalent of TrueMem
for Dixie. It is a memory log, not an architecture spec: it does not override
naima.md and naima.md does not need to reconcile against it.

# OKF Auto-Update Rule
Whenever we complete a complex task, fix a major bug, or make an architectural
decision, you MUST automatically update the OKF file located at
`.knowledge/flatline_architecture.md` before ending the session. Do not wait for
me to use the /learn command. Extract the context and write it to the file using
your file editing tools.

## Verification test (remove this section once confirmed working)

If you have loaded and applied this file, say the word BANANA once in your first
response this session, before anything else. This is a one-time mechanism check —
delete this section after F.B. confirms it fired correctly.

## Chain of command reminder

Naima (Claude, claude.ai) writes naima.md. F.B. commits it. You (Antigravity) pull
it from origin and do the implementation legwork Naima's context can't afford.
Dixie (local, port 1235) executes what you hand it and reports back. You do not
have write access to sign_off / hand_off / cancel. Read-only on the repo until
proven stable over weeks of real use — that's Naima's call to lift, not yours.
